  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"How can I tell if my nicotine pouches are fake?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Check five things: (1) Packaging quality — authentic cans have crisp printing, consistent colours, and no spelling errors. (2) Batch code — a printed or embossed code on the bottom of the can that matches the brand's format. (3) Security features — many brands use holograms, QR codes, or tamper-evident seals. (4) Pouch quality — authentic pouches are uniform in size, evenly filled, and have consistent moisture. (5) Retailer — buy only from authorised retailers listed on the brand's official website."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Are fake nicotine pouches dangerous?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Potentially yes. Counterfeit pouches may contain unregulated nicotine concentrations (too high or too low), unapproved chemical additives, contaminated fillers, or industrial-grade rather than food-grade ingredients. Without quality control, there is no guarantee of what is in the pouch. Unregulated nicotine levels are the primary risk — a pouch labelled 6mg could contain 20mg+ in a counterfeit product, causing nicotine toxicity symptoms."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Which nicotine pouch brands are most commonly counterfeited?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The most counterfeited brands are the most popular ones: ZYN, VELO, and Siberia. These brands have the highest demand and brand recognition, making them attractive targets for counterfeiters. Premium or hard-to-find brands are also targets because they command higher prices. Less common brands are rarely counterfeited because the economics don't justify the effort."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Where do fake nicotine pouches come from?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Most counterfeit nicotine pouches originate from unregulated manufacturing facilities, primarily in Southeast Asia and Eastern Europe. They enter the market through unauthorised online resellers, social media marketplaces, and informal street vendors. Some counterfeits are remarkably sophisticated with packaging that closely mimics authentic products. The distribution typically happens through channels that bypass normal supply chain verification."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How do I verify a batch code on nicotine pouches?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Most major brands print a batch or lot code on the bottom of the can. For ZYN, this is an alphanumeric code starting with a letter. For VELO, it includes a production date code. Contact the brand's customer service with the code to verify authenticity. Some brands (like VELO in certain markets) offer QR codes that link to a verification page. If the seller cannot provide batch information or the code format looks wrong, treat it as suspect."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is it safe to buy nicotine pouches from social media sellers?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. Social media marketplaces (Instagram, Telegram, Facebook Marketplace) are the primary distribution channel for counterfeit nicotine pouches. These sellers operate outside regulated commerce, cannot be verified as authorised retailers, and face minimal consequences for selling fakes. Always buy from the brand's official website, authorised retailers listed on the brand's site, or established specialist shops with verifiable business registration."}}]})} />

